                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3sb3xj7f/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p><hi rend=\"underline\">no man</hi> in this world would I be so happy\n                                        as to embrace and make my<lb/> friend and companion like\n                                        yourself—we have not your equal here who can<lb/> work for\n                                        the Jew cause as yourself, your learning, your information;\n                                        but it is<lb/> not a market for <hi rend=\"underline\">genuine\n                                                  Gold</hi>. They <sic>dont</sic> want it, anything\n                                                  <hi rend=\"underline\">brass</hi>, <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">copper</hi> &amp;c<lb/> so that\n                                        it has a gloss <add>דרך אמונה</add> as for literature\n                                                  <sic>dont</sic> talk of it. I know what my<lb/>\n                                        old friend the great <persName>Solomon Bennett</persName>\n                                        suffered who had <hi rend=\"underline\">sterling</hi> works,\n                                        was it not for<lb/> the Christian friends would his work on\n                                        the Temple &amp; Engraving be out—or his<lb/> judge by my\n                                                  <hi rend=\"underline\">small</hi> &amp;\n                                                  <sic>triffling</sic> portion of the <add>נר\n                                                  ישראל</add> which I merely published to put<lb/>\n                                        them to the trial, who came forward to uphold me and say let\n                                        it published? it certainly<lb/> was not <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  >Dedicated</hi> to some <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  >one</hi>—but made all my brethren poor &amp; rich\n                                                  <hi rend=\"underline\">one</hi>; 1000<lb/> are spent\n                                        to get <hi rend=\"underline\">honors</hi> &amp; <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">titles</hi>. I have sent you my\n                                        Dr. Sir a small sermon<lb/> through the hand of\n                                                  <persName>Mr. Hart</persName> which no doubt you\n                                        have received. I have<lb/> had no answer still from the said\n                                        gentlemen on my second letter to him <date>19th<lb/>\n                                                  Adar</date> a reply to his remarks my conclusion\n                                        to him was as follows \"I addressed<lb/> myself to you\n                                        candidly as a person of high station and reputation, and\n                                        also<lb/> as a friend of <persName>Revd. Mr.\n                                                  Leeser</persName> of whom I have formed a very\n                                        high opinion<lb/> and for whom I entertain great respect,\n                                        admiring his talents, and<lb/> conceiving him to be a man\n                                        worthy of honor and a <add>על כל פשעים תכסה אהבה</add>\n                                        &amp;c and with<lb/> your own words \"that He has done more\n                                        for the Jews in <placeName>America</placeName> than any<lb/>\n                                        other Hazan.\" and who after 20 years in office, and now\n                                        should<lb/> be <hi rend=\"underline\">out</hi> of <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">office</hi>, I cannot but regard\n                                        not only with regret—but as a<lb/> calamity.\" and I\n                                        continued that even some little you might<lb/> have been in\n                                        the fault for <hi rend=\"underline\">publishing</hi>—I fully\n                                        trusted &amp; looked <hi rend=\"underline\">from\n                                        him</hi>,<lb/> and he might make use of my name to the whole\n                                        of the congregation<lb/> regarding you <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  ><add>נצטדק מה נאמר מה נדבר מה</add></hi> the love\n                                        they <hi rend=\"underline\">should</hi> cherish &amp; entertain<lb/>\n                                        <hi rend=\"underline\">for a great man like yourself and who\n                                                  for 20 years instructed them the</hi><lb/>\n                                        <hi rend=\"underline\">word of God</hi>. I hope some of the\n                                        words may have an effect. I solemnly<lb/> declare to you\n                                        that I never felt for any one or God per your treatment.<lb/>\n                                        <add>תעורר את ליבם לב האבן</add>—I would at once make\n                                        friends with <persName>Mr. H.</persName> for really he<lb/>\n                                        <add>למען תגבר עליהם ויהיה שלום בחילך שלוה בארמונותיך</add>\n                                        appears to have been <hi rend=\"underline\">your friend</hi>.\n                                        I shall copy you his language<lb/> in his letter <date>25th\n                                                  Shebat</date>. \"When at the time he wrote the\n                                        article he was aware</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3sb3xj7f/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
